name: Gulf Coast Social Services
details:
Welcome to Gulf Coast Social Services. I am proud and excited to say that this year marks the Agency’s 30th anniversary of providing quality, community-based services to children and adults in Louisiana who have a variety of challenges. Gulf Coast continues to strive to expand our existing services and develop new and innovative programs that will improve the lives of those we serve. We are fortunate to have qualified and committed staff whose focus is on the development and well-being of the individuals we serve, with an outcome of living as independently as possible in the community.

As we look to the future, there is no shortage of challenges on the horizon. However, as always, we will continue to strive to provide the highest quality of care to all those we serve.

If you would like any additional information or you feel that we can be of service to you or a family member, please feel free to contact us at our Corporate Office in Metairie or any one of our Regional Offices throughout the state.

name: Edisen House Children's Center, Metairie Park Country Day School
details:
The Edisen House Children's Center, located on Country Day's campus, is filled with warmth and energy. It is a place where children blossom, where parents will often be found, and where attachments are formed that continue from one year to the next.

Our philosophy is based on the fact that children learn best by being active participants in constructing their knowledge. For this reason, they are given every opportunity to play and explore in a stimulating environment. They are encouraged to explore the properties of water by playing with objects and seeing which ones sink or float. They learn about art by watching a visiting artist mix colors and then trying it themselves. They learn what the terms rough and smooth mean by using their fingers to compare the texture of flour to oats. Edisen House is an active place and everyone, from infants to pre-K students, takes part.

Because it is located on Country Day's campus, our children have the luxury of acres of land on which to play and explore. Even the youngest students go on "field trips" to take a peek at what's happening elsewhere on campus. There might be a local author reading to students, a troupe of flamenco dancers performing in the auditorium, or students performing carols during the holidays. We have many incredible opportunities simply because of our location.

What we love the most about Edisen House, though, is the dedication of our teachers. They are the reason that learning is fun, that our children are so excited about coming, and that joy is ever-present. They are the heart of Edisen House, and they have created an atmosphere that is filled with warmth and enthusiasm. In addition, our teachers are experienced, knowledgeable, and continually developing themselves professionally. They are interested in the lives of their students and serious about the work they do each day. Edisen House teachers believe in the uniqueness of each child and strive to match activities with individual needs.

name: Ascension Parish Head Start - Site 1
details:
The Office of Head Start (OHS) advises the Assistant Secretary for Children and Families on issues regarding the Head Start program (including Early Head Start). The Office develops legislative and budgetary proposals; identifies areas for research, demonstration, and developmental activities; presents operational planning objectives and initiatives relating to Head Start to the Assistant Secretary for Administration for Children and Families; and oversees the progress of approved activities. OHS provides leadership and coordination for the activities of the Head Start program in the ACF Central Office including the Head Start Regional Program Units. The Office represents Head Start in inter-agency activities with other Federal and non-Federal organizations.

Early Head Start promotes healthy prenatal outcomes, enhances the development of infants and toddlers, and promotes healthy family functioning.

The mission of Elisabetta Renzi Child Development Center is to provide a loving, caring, Christian environment for children. The Center is owned and administered by the Sisters of Our Lady of Sorrow, a Congregation of religious women. As a result, Gospel values play a big role in the life of the Center, mindful that education without some knowledge of God is not complete.

The concern of the Center is to educate the whole child: spiritual, intellectual, emotional and physical.

We believe in giving the child the freedom to explore and experience in a rich, stimulating, environment with the guidance from the teachers. The child will learn eagerly, lead by his or her own natural curiosity and desire to understand the world. The future of the child is based on the experience of his or her early years, therefore we believe in helping the child:

    to feel good about oneself
    to develop a sense of worth
    to see joy in the goodness and beauty of the world
    to have the ability to trust others
    to give oneself through sharing and helping

name: Young Years Children's Education Center
details:
Welcome to Young Years, a quality-learning center located in southeast Shreveport, Louisiana - a truly new, innovative and affordable concept in childcare and preschool education.

32 years of consistently working to improve the program, Young Years full-time education and childcare center offers the finest facilities available for children ages 30 months to 12 years.

Young Years has been hand-selected by the Department of Education (ED) to be a Louisiana test site for the recently developed pre-school HATCH Program. Using the "Big Day for Pre-K" curriculum in conjunction with ED's HATCH Program and the Young Years Tutor-by-Two's Program, Young Years' kindergarten prep program is designed for 2-1/2 to 5 year olds preparing them for their all-important school years ahead. We are excited to announce that 100% of Young Years' students that applied and tested for the 2013 Caddo Parish Magnet Program were accepted!

We offer an extensive school-age program for before and after school with planned activities and sports to keep students busy with age appropriate groupings of ages 5-to-7 and 8-to-12 year olds.

name: La Petite Ecole Child Care
details:
The Environment
At La Petite Ecole, we strive to provide a clean, safe and educational environment for young children. Within our care, children develop skills that promote physical, emotional, social and intellectual growth. Our daily routine is intended to stimulate a child’s interest through books, pictures, music, songs, science, arts and crafts, friends, play and field trips. We further believe that within our environment, children can thrive and have the opportunity to blossom into responsible and contributing members of our society.

Our Staff
We have been blessed with wonderful staff over the 32 years we have been open. We have five full time staff members that have been working at La Petite Ecole for a total of 135 years. That averages to 27 years each at the same center! We require on-going training for our staff through classes they attend to continue their education revolving around children. Additionally, our staff maintains certificates in First Aid and CPR.

Our Philosophy
La Petite Ecole is dedicated and committed to our children by providing exceptional education and quality child care. It is our philosophy to focus on the needs of the individual child by providing a stimulating atmosphere for learning along with a secure loving environment. Our intentions will focus on providing opportunities for children to learn good health habits, waiting turns, obeying rules, being good leaders and followers, taking care of personal belongings, cleaning up, accepting responsibilities, and having emotional control. We are passionate about education and providing our children with the tools to be successful in life.

name: Gethsemane LaPetite Early Childhood Development Center
details:
Choosing childcare is one of the most important decisions you will make in your child’s life. The care they receive in these foundational years set the stage for the duration of the education process.

                At Gethsemane LaPetite, we believe each child deserves to grow and learn at his/her own pace. Our responsibility as a childcare center of Early Education is to provide the tools and the environment that will give every child the opportunity to develop to their greatest potential. Children deserve to receive all the support and respect it takes to establish a strong foundation for their future. We do all of this in a safe, clean, nurturing, State approved Christian environment that is both fun and exciting for children.

                Making Learning fun and exciting is just one of the ways we’re able to develop each child’s potential. The other is to focus on the three key educational platforms for children: Cognitive, Social and Physical; or as we say, “Learn, Play, and Grow”!

                With all we have to offer here at Gethsemane LaPetite Early Childhood Development Center your child is guaranteed the opportunity to grow into a well-rounded individual with the appropriate education to be respected and ultimately MAKE A DIFFERENCE.

details:
The Office of Head Start (OHS) advises the Assistant Secretary for Children and Families on issues regarding the Head Start program (including Early Head Start). The Office develops legislative and budgetary proposals; identifies areas for research, demonstration, and developmental activities; presents operational planning objectives and initiatives relating to Head Start to the Assistant Secretary for Administration for Children and Families; and oversees the progress of approved activities. OHS provides leadership and coordination for the activities of the Head Start program in the ACF Central Office including the Head Start Regional Program Units. The Office represents Head Start in inter-agency activities with other Federal and non-Federal organizations.

Early Head Start promotes healthy prenatal outcomes, enhances the development of infants and toddlers, and promotes healthy family functioning.

Structured activiities will include the use of a pre-school curriculum and to have a daily choice of Learning Centers such as Library, Arts and Crafts, Music, Math, Manipulatives, Science/Sand Water Play, Blocks, Housekeeping and Writing Area which provide a variety of ready availaible toys. Studies show that these types of activities nurture a sense of well-being and belonging in children and contribute dramatically towards the development of self-esteem. name: Hume Child Development Center, Inc.
details:
Founded in 1911 by the Reverend Henderson Dunn, Hume Child Development Center is one of the oldest pre-school education centers designed to serve African American children in the South and probably in the country. During his pastorate at Central Congregational Church, Reverend Dunn recognized the pressing need of black families to have a safe place to leave their children while they worked. The Center is additionally an outgrowth of a community program begun at Central by Isabella Hume, a teacher at Straight College and an assistant pastor at the church, to assist black mothers.

Hume Center was originally housed in the basement of the old Central Congregational Church at Liberty and Cleveland Streets in New Orleans and called the Colored Day Nursery. In 1931, the Center moved to the Daniel Hand School building on the Straight College grounds at Rocheblave and Canal Streets and its name was changed to honor Miss Hume. Since 1954, the Center has occupied its present space at 319 North Tonti Street.

Central has sponsored Hume since its beginning; however, a non-denominational Board of Directors drawn from the community governs the Center’s operations. The Center was incorporated in 1975 as an independent agency and offers programs for students from 15 months to 5 years of age. During the 1960's, Hume’s services were expanded to incorporate after school programs for students aged 6 to 12.

Under the leadership of a new Director, Helen Smith Green and a small staff, we have re-opened as of November 1, 2007. Our staff is very dedicated and many of the pre-Katrina faculty have returned to Hume Center. Additionally, most of our administrative staff have donated their services for almost a year to help the Center get started.

In 1985, the owners of Kids Kampus decided to take a chance and expand. The first step was to physically expand; They purchased 3 lots and built a 4500 square foot building. The next step was to increase the number of children in attendance; Kids Kampus reopened, licensed for 98 students with attendance at full capacity.

Throughout the past 30 years Kids Kampus Learning Center has remained dedicated to their children, from the babies to the after-care students. It was this dedication that gave the owners & teachers the motivation to rebuild after hurricane Katrina. Kids Kampus Learning Center reopened after just one year (Sept. '06) with a full house! Since then Kids Kampus has continued to ensure that the children of St. Bernard Parish receive excellent care in an educational environment. Our teachers provide the care and guidance essential to the formative years. Messiah Montessori is an accredited Montessori nonpublic school approved by the Louisiana Department of Education; certified by the Louisiana Montessori Association; a Member School of the International Montessori Council; and an educational ministry of the non-denominational Harvest Cathedral. details:
The mission of the Florida Parishes Juvenile Detention Center is to provide a safe and restrictive environment for juveniles requiring secure residential detention and to insure that those detained will be available for scheduled court hearings.

The youth’s medical, dental and mental health needs will be handled as necessary on an emergency or immediate care basis. The detention program shall facilitate a continuum of care by providing necessary referrals for follow-up services.

name: Calcasieu Parish Office of Juvenile Justice Services
details: It is the mission of the Juvenile Detention Center to provide consistent, temporary, secure confinement and quality rehabilitative services designed for juvenile offenders and their families in a manner that is responsive to their needs, while always being mindful of public safety. The Juvenile Detention Center provides temporary secure confinement and care to juveniles referred from local law enforcement agencies, state agencies, Federal Agencies and from our own Probation, Drug Court and F.I.N.S. departments. The center is equipped to house 36 juveniles, male and female, ranging from 10 to 20 years of age.  The Juvenile Detention Center was opened in 1968. The center is located on the north side of the Office of Juvenile Justice Services at 3615 East Prien Lake Road. The facility consists of 18 rooms, 2 observation rooms, 2 recreation rooms, a control room for staff, laundry room, kitchen, nurse's office, 2 classrooms and 2 fenced recreation yards. A computer lab and library are located in the recreation rooms. The Juvenile Detention Center staff consists of a Manager of Detention, Assistant Manager of Detention, Nurse, Food Service Manager, Shift Supervisors, Detention Officers, Cooks and Maintenance personnel.  A Master's Level Counselor provides counseling, suicide screening and assessments for the detention center. In addition, a local psychologist provides consultation to the staff regarding juveniles who have mental health and substance abuse problems. In 2013, the Center was licensed by the Louisiana Department of Children and Family Services.

details:
Chloris Faulkner purchased land in June 2007 in hopes that one day she could open a childcare center where families can access educational childcare that prepares children for success in school and life.
 
“After several years of planning, meetings, and set-backs, construction finally began in December 2009,” said Faulkner. The Faulkners held a dedication and ribbon cutting ceremony on July 17, 2010 and began accepting children later that month.
 
The childcare center, located at 801 St. John Street in Monroe, LA, currently has seven employees. The childcare center operates from 6am to 12 noon Monday through Saturday with open enrollment. 
 
“The staff at the LSBDC at University of Louisiana Monroe assisted me with a business plan to assess the feasibility of the day care facility, “ said Faulkner. “They also put me in contact with a non-traditional lender, Enterprise Corporation of the Delta, who helped finance the construction.”

name: Edisen House Children's Center - Baby
details:
The Edisen House Children's Center, located on Country Day's campus, is filled with warmth and energy. It is a place where children blossom, where parents will often be found, and where attachments are formed that continue from one year to the next.

Our philosophy is based on the fact that children learn best by being active participants in constructing their knowledge. For this reason, they are given every opportunity to play and explore in a stimulating environment. They are encouraged to explore the properties of water by playing with objects and seeing which ones sink or float. They learn about art by watching a visiting artist mix colors and then trying it themselves. They learn what the terms rough and smooth mean by using their fingers to compare the texture of flour to oats. Edisen House is an active place and everyone, from infants to pre-K students, takes part.

Because it is located on Country Day's campus, our children have the luxury of acres of land on which to play and explore. Even the youngest students go on "field trips" to take a peek at what's happening elsewhere on campus. There might be a local author reading to students, a troupe of flamenco dancers performing in the auditorium, or students performing carols during the holidays. We have many incredible opportunities simply because of our location.

What we love the most about Edisen House, though, is the dedication of our teachers. They are the reason that learning is fun, that our children are so excited about coming, and that joy is ever-present. They are the heart of Edisen House, and they have created an atmosphere that is filled with warmth and enthusiasm. In addition, our teachers are experienced, knowledgeable, and continually developing themselves professionally. They are interested in the lives of their students and serious about the work they do each day. Edisen House teachers believe in the uniqueness of each child and strive to match activities with individual needs.

name: DeColores Adoptions International
details:
DeColores Adoptions International is a nonprofit state licensed adoption agency located in Lake Charles, Louisiana. DAI received full Hague Convention accreditation by the Council on Accreditation (COA).  DeColores Adoptions International´s founders are no strangers to the international adoption world. Twin sisters, Sandy Arredondo and Debbie Campbell are adoptive parents themselves of children from Paraguay, Guatemala, and the United States.

DeColores Adoptions International specializes in domestic adoptions and international adoption programs. It is dedicated to providing loving, adoptive families here in the U.S. to children from the U.S. (domestic adoptions) and other countries (international adoptions). We began our work as a result of our love and commitment to the orphans, and to the parents who long to share their love and their lives with a child. We offer adoptions services nationwide

DeColores Adoptions International believes that God calls us, as parents, to care for and nurture His children because they are His greatest creation, but sometimes they are born unto unfortunate circumstances which in turn fill orphanages and foster homes with beautiful newborn babies and toddlers. We are committed to providing assistance to these wonderful waiting children.

We work endlessly to find loving families who have always hoped and dreamed to share permanent and loving home for these children of God, which ultimately makes this our highest calling.

DeColores Adoptions International is also committed to providing extensive support, security, and empathy to birth mothers and adoptive families on a personal level of compassion and understanding. We will continuously strive hard to provide each birth mother, and family who adopts through our agency, ongoing guidance and support to accomplish these goals, making the entire adoption experience a reward of love and happiness that last a lifetime!

name: A Place to Grow Learning Center
ACDS Inc. Brook's Child Development Head Start
details:
Head Start is a Federal program for preschool children and their families whose income falls at or below the Federal Income guidelines. This includes children who have been determined to have a disability. The Head Start program is operated by a team of professionals. These professionals have a wide variety of experience in the Head Start program, early childhood practices and believe in a developmentally appropriate environment for preschoolers. Head Start has been in existence in Avoyelles Parish since 1965.
    
    Our program works with both the child and  the family to provide a variety of educational activities. The children also receive medical and dental care, healthy nutritious meals and snacks, indoor activities as well as enjoying the outdoors in a safe environment. Services are offered to meet the special needs with disabilities.
    
    Our program provides children with activities that help them grow mentally, socially, emotionally and physically. Our Staff realizes that the first and most important teachers of the children are their parents. We welcome your involvement in Head Start activities and will work as partners with you to help your child progress forward.

details:
Leave your worries behind when your little ones stay and play at our day care center. At Coteau's Little Cuties LLC in New Iberia, Louisiana, we're the children's day care that truly cares. For a day care and learning center serving children ages 6 months to 4 years old, you're unlikely to find a more caring or better-prepared education program than ours.
Kids need good, quality care, and that doesn't change just because your budget is tight. We offer affordable day care for all budgets, and have an application and registration process that respects your financial situation. Give your kids the gift of a high-quality educational and care experience with our professional and well-trained staff.

name: Country Day School of Baton Rouge
details:
For over thirty years, Country Day School has served the families of our community through the education and nurturing of children. Our school began as an early childhood program, later expanding to include elementary grades kindergarten through fifth at our mid-town campus. In addition to our mid town campus preschool, there are three CDS early childhood programs located in the south Baton Rouge area.

What makes our school different? We believe that each child is a unique individual with experiences, abilities, talents and feelings all his own. It is our mission to preserve this uniqueness while providing opportunities for children to be part of a learning community. Our state Class A early childhood program and our state-accredited elementary program are designed not merely to help a child acquire information, but to help them learn to think independently, draw conclusions, express their thoughts, and to respect the ideas of others. We believe the early experiences in a child’s education will establish the foundation for a lifetime of learning. Our mission is to make a difference one child at a time.

Our school is composed of eight classes funded by different resources. We have five LA-4 classes, one Title I class, one 8(g) class and one brand new three-year old program. The three-year old class is funded by Special Populations.

Our Preschool program can help prepare your child for success in school and in life. Learning research shows how important the early years are in a child's learning and development. Parents we need your help! When you have home and school working together, it equals a successful child. We want to be your partner with ensuring your child acquires the skills, attitudes, and habits to succeed in school and throughout life

That is why everything we learn and know we are happy to share with you through phone calls, teacher conferences, parent open house nights, website blogs and social media updates. After all, raising our kids to be the best they can be is the ultimate achievement of a parent and care giver, and together, we can do just that!

name: GIGGLES 'N' GRINS PRESCHOOL AND EARLY EDUCATION CENTER
ARM CHRISTIAN SCHOOL
details:
On January 1, 2006, Apostolic Restoration Ministry (ARM) was born with 25 members in the home of Pastor and First Lady Porter.
 
 In nine months, 10 souls were saved and many were baptized. The Lord also blessed the congregation with a new church home in South Jackson.  The property is located at 2801 Oak Forest Drive, and became the home of Apostolic Restoration Ministry for three years.  During these three years the Lord blessed ARM’s with many gifts. He rose up Sunday School teachers, deacons, ushers, singers, ministers, praise dancers, musicians and video and audio technicians. In December 2007, Pastor Porter started a prison ministry teaching Bible classes every Tuesday and Thursday.
 
In July 2009, we were blessed to purchase our present facility. The facility sits on slightly more than 3 acres of  land  and consists of an 800–850 seat sanctuary, and several additional spaces, including a gymnasium. 
Our History

“The devil tried to shatter my vision when the church was sat on fire,” says Pastor Porter.  “It was Sunday, October 26, 2008. Deacon Manyfield had just remarked, ‘We are out-growing our clothes (referring to our then-current location).  It is time for us to make a move.’  After services dismissed, the saints were sitting and fellowshipping, when someone came into the church and yelled,  ‘That church y’all want is on fire.’  As I stood there watching the church go up in flames, the thought came to my mind that God is a God that answereth by FIRE! They meant it for our bad...but God meant it for our good.”
 
The saints of God held on to the vision and with a handful of people, (less than 150) the Lord blessed us to purchase our present facility, which was originally appraised at $1.3 million, for a fraction of the price. The extent of the fire damage was to the pulpit area only. On Easter Sunday, April 4, 2010, the ARM family held its first service in the small sanctuary. The facility was finished within 6 weeks and cost the saints approximately $110,000 in renovation. The Lord blessed us with a score of volunteers, including professional contractors, to partner with the ARM's family and complete this project.   With the help of the Lord, the ARM family will soon begin restoring the main sanctuary soon.

name: CREATIVE MINDS LEARNING CENTER # 1
details:
Creative Minds Learning Centers (CMLC) was founded by the Mckinster family in 1997 due to an overwhelming demand for high quality preschool programs.

Creative Minds operates seven eco-friendly and certified preschools and child development centers in the Portland, Metropolitan Area. Our schools are proud to offer media-free educational and healthy environments with the children's interests and parent's needs in mind. Creative Minds’ mission is to provide a progressive preschool program that helps foster life-long learning and developmental growth.

Creative Minds Learning Centers have been designed to encourage children to explore their interests in a creative and artistic setting. Certified with the State of Oregon and members of NAEYC, OAEYC, Oregon Environmental Council and other Early Childhood organizations, CMLC schools provide a progressive and positive environment for children, staff and families. Creative Minds has also been recognized as members of QRIS, selected as one of 25 Oregon Program of Quality schools and continues to be a leader in the Early Childhood Education field.

Our philosophy is to enrich children's lives with creative arts and accredited educational materials while developing self esteem, confidence and a sense of independence. While there are many approaches and "labels" for teaching young children, Creative Minds schools focuses on the basis of early childhood development being "trichotomized" into a trio of goals: (1) social/emotional development and (2) intellectual development and (3) the acquisition of meaningful and useful academic skills. Children are capable and willing to learn and naturally can begin to read at Pre-Kindergarten grade. It is our duty to guide the children during the day in a structured setting. The children depend on the security of a daily routine and come to school excited to see their friends and teachers.

name: MOTHER GOOSE INC.
details:
Welcome to Mother Goose Christian School web site! We carefully plan each day to nurture and support your child's growth and development. We provide affordable, high-quality, child care and comprehensive support services for children and their families with respect for individual differences. We serve children from age 6 weeks to 7 years. We provide Summer Camp activities for children 2 years to 10 years.

At Mother Goose, we follow a consistent yet flexible daily routine that gives infants, toddlers, and young children plenty of opportunities for active play, stimulating explorations, personal decision making, and preparation for lifelong learning!

Call Mother Goose, A place where children come to receive a strong academic foundation. We provide a validated, research-based program that allows for each child to develop at his or her own pace. That's the uniqueness of our program. Children are allowed to work on their individual levels. The contents of our program are aligned with local, state, and national standards.

name: MOORE COMMUNITY HOUSE EARLY HEAD START-DAVIS CENTER
details:
The MCH Early Headstart Program provides early childhood and comprehensive healthand fafamily support services to low income families, as well as support for teen parents. By doingso, we open up opportunities for lo income parents to work and go to school, while at the same time offering valuable learning experiences for their children.

 The MCH Child Care Food Program provides each enrolled child with nutritious food and supports nutrition education. Our Comprehensive Family Services councelors assess the specific needs of individual families and then develop a holistic approach that responds directly to those needs. Our Expectant Mothers Program offers parenting training and gives expectant mothers experience with toddlers and infants. Following birth, MCH works with the mother and child over a three year journey of positive development. Finally, MCH helps build relationships between women and employers through Employment and Training Referrals for parents of children in our Early Headstart program. Together, these programs offer our families the support they need to break the cycle of poverty.

The Ray of Sunshine Learning Center believes that the most important years of a child’s brain development occur from infancy until age five.
 
We provide purposeful play which is a significant contributor to intellectual, emotional, language and social development.  There is no doubt that a curriculum is needed to teach skills for school success.
 
We believe young children should be mostly taught in a playful manner rather than by only sitting and listening to a teacher.  We take advantage of both short and long-term school achievments which can be affected by the early development of cognitive and social skills.
 
Ray of Sunshine Learning Center takes advantage of the windows of opportunity in these early years to give your child the best start toward a lifetime of learning.

Attitudes and confidence developed during a child's formative years serve the child throughout his or her entire lifetime.
Through the Montessori experience, the teacher and the students become partners in an environment of discovery and investigative learning. Students are given time to organically process information, building skills that will exponentially increase their capacity for knowledge and problem solving. The environment is a blend of materials, technology, hypothesis and experimentation, which sets the stage for learning at it's most basic and exciting level!

The purpose of the ECLC is to provide opportunities which meet the educational need of the early childhood years in a Christian environment for children in the community. Realizing that in the first 6 years of life a child forms his or her basic patterns for coping with life, the church provides an educational program which considers the developmental needs of the child and emphasizes growth in all areas -- physical, emotional, mental, and spiritual.

hoosing a school for your preschool child is one of the most exciting and challenging decisions you will make in these early years. We look forward to meeting and serving you.

details:
ABC & Me Christian Preschool & Daycare understands that it can be difficult leaving your child with someone unfamiliar to you, especially an infant. Unfortunately many families are dependent on both parents working outside of the home, for that reason we offer a safe and reliable environment for children of all ages. Parents can feel secure knowing that their child will be well provided for at our facility.

Our facility was founded with the sole intention of creating a school committed to small class sizes, individual attention for all students, daily interaction with parents and the development of a well-rounded child. ABC & Me Christian Preschool & Daycare offers daycare for child birth thru thirteen years of age with special infant care and preschool programs to assure your child reaches their developmental goals and is ready to advance to the next level. Our students leave this facility academically, emotionally, and socially ready for the next step in their lives.

Our preschool abides to all health and safety practices and safety guidelines. You can trust your children with our friendly staff and clean atmosphere. We are trained and ready to provide excellent care for your child. At ABC & Me Christian Preschool & Daycare our child care specialists understand each child has his or her own personality and individual needs.

We provide individual attention to all children and make sure to give accurate updated reports to parents when they arrive to pick up their child. If you have any questions or comments regarding our childcare facility please feel free to contact us. We are always more than happy to serve Columbus, MS, and its surrounding cities.

name: ABC CHILD DEVELOPMENT CENTER OF BILOXI, LLC
ABC CHILD DEVELOPMENT CENTER OF OCEAN SPRINGS
details:
Welcome to ABC Child Development Center of Ocean Springs. I am pleased that you have taken the time to visit our website.
My name is Janet Bentzinger and I have been working with children in a preschool setting, or as a nurse, for over 30 years. The passion I have for children has never wavered in all of these years, and I feel very fortunate to have the opportunity to introduce each prospective parent to our center. The facility will assist parents by providing the best care in a loving environment with the resources to stimulate your child's imagination, thereby, allowing their cognitive skills to abound.
 Within the facility's daily schedule, each child has the opportunities to create, explore the environment, learn problem solving, personal interaction skills, and learning concepts through first-hand experience. Children develop a positive self-concept through a balance of self and teacher directed activities.
Opportunities for solitary play as well as group activities are provided. Staff serves as a positive role model and provides care that is supportive, nurturing, warm and responsive to each child’s individual needs. We respect parents as the primary and most important provider of care and nurturing, and we believe parents and teachers are partners in the children’s care and education.

name: AIKEN VILLAGE PRESCHOOL
details: Located in a quiet corner of the campus of Mississippi State University, Aiken Village Preschool is a year-round, campus-based early childhood program for children ages 3 to 5 years. The preschool is accredited by the National Association for the Education of Young Children (NAEYC) and holds a 5-Star rating in Quality Stars, Mississippi’s tiered quality rating and improvement system. The MSU Early Childhood Institute (ECI) operates Aiken Village Preschool, which serves as a Head Start collaboration site in partnership with the Institute of Community Services, Inc.  Aiken Village Preschool offers a developmentally appropriate child-oriented curriculum, meeting the needs of the whole child through play-based early learning experiences. The play environment provides many opportunities for exploring, experimenting, problem-solving, communicating, and cooperating. Research has shown that young children who are supported in their social, emotional, physical, and cognitive development have lasting social and academic success in kindergarten and beyond

Asbury Playschool seeks to make the children in our care feel at home in God’s world by providing activities that are developmentally appropriate.

Our program incorporates a variety of learning opportunities including story time, crafts, music, outdoor play, movement, and creative expression. Our main goal is to provide an environment, shaped by our Christian faith, which allows children to grow up into the fullness of God’s image.

Most classrooms have four computers for students to use during the school day. Students have access to a fully automated library and media center as well. A Variety of educational programs such as after-school tutoring, enrichment courses, and online curricula provide students with a wealth of opportunity to excel and achieve. Each teacher can better meet student needs as well with data warehousing resources developed by district personnel. These resources allow teachers to profile the past performance of a student and better meet the specific needs of the individual student.

BOGUE CHITTO EARLY CHILDHOOD CENTER
details:
It is the belief of the Division of Early Childhood Education that education is more than academic achievement and must provide learning experiences for all Tribal members, from infants to elders. It must include not only the intellectual but the democratic, moral, personal, physical, and social development of the Mississippi Band of Choctaw Indians.
The DOECE recognizes that true success and achievement will only be accomplished through the combined efforts of home and school. The DOECE accepts the primary responsibility for guiding the learning process while reinforcing the need for support and involvement from the parents and the community, for the first and most important teachers of our children are the parents.
The DOECE feels that its bilingual/cultural curriculum implementation and other provided services help to encourage and guide the child toward success in today's society, while instilling in them pride in themselves and their heritage.

details: Since 1950, Coast Episcopal School has offered an educational program that is unsurpassed among schools on the Mississippi Gulf Coast. Daily chapel services, religion classes, and the presence of a school chaplain reinforce the spiritual dimension of our everyday life. These academic, fine arts, enrichment and spiritual initiatives support a school culture that celebrates the great ideas of teaching and learning, purpose and meaning.

details:
Friends of Children of Mississippi (FCM), Inc. is a highly efficient, team-based, non-profit human service organization.

    Assisting families to become self-sufficient and serving as advocates for children and families.

We increase families’ capacity to support and nurture their children by developing a compassionate partnership between staff and families, which recognizes parents as the primary educators of their children.

In support of this partnership, FCM, Inc. provides opportunities for continuous staff development and growth and creates an environment that promotes job satisfaction and community service.

name: CONEHATTA EARLY CHILDHOOD CENTER
details:
Vision Statement
To provide a comprehensive, inter-disciplinary approach to services including education, health, nutrition, social services, and parent involvement.
Mission Statement
It is the belief of the Division of Early Childhood Education that education is more than academic achievement and must provide learning experiences for all Tribal members, from infants to elders. It must include not only the intellectual but the democratic, moral, personal, physical, and social development of the Mississippi Band of Choctaw Indians.
The DOECE recognizes that true success and achievement will only be accomplished through the combined efforts of home and school. The DOECE accepts the primary responsibility for guiding the learning process while reinforcing the need for support and involvement from the parents and the community, for the first and most important teachers of our children are the parents.
The DOECE feels that its bilingual/cultural curriculum implementation and other provided services help to encourage and guide the child toward success in today's society, while instilling in them pride in themselves and their heritage.

name: COVENANT PRESBYTERIAN PRESCHOOL
details:
Covenant Presbyterian Preschool provides a morning preschool for ages two to five years. The program is designed to nurture each child in every area of development: spiritual, social, intellectual, physical, and emotional.

The philosophy of the school is one of commitment to the Christian nurture of each child to an awareness of his/her soul, his/her response to God and to the recognition of his/her uniqueness in God's sight. Recognizing that very young children need to experience God's love daily through others, the staff Covenant Preschool are Christians whose love for God radiates through them to the children.  The teachers are those who believe their teaching is a gift that God has given them.

Interwoven into the preschool program is an inclusion program for children with special needs. Each child is provided a normal preschool experience and encouraged to participate in all activities.  In addition, he/she may receive speech therapy and special education instruction from qualified staff.  The preschool determines the needs of the preschool-age child and plans the program that will meet those needs.

The preschool provides a safe, healthful and attractive setting wherein a desirable preschool education can take place. In other words, it provides a rich, full and happy school environment promoting the development of each child to his/her fullest potential in relation to age and needs.

name: CRADLE TO CRAYONS II
details:
We welcome you and your child to our childcare and learning center. You have honored us by choosing our center to care for your most cherished possession. In these first years, your child’s experiences will lay the foundation for what he or she can become in later years. We shall strive together, to develop trust and a sense of security, which is so vital in the early years to his or her development as a whole person.

Through the love of Jesus in the lives of our staff, your child will have experiences that will help him or her be better prepared socially, mentally, physically, and spiritually for today and the days ahead. Your child’s needs are our utmost concern, and we welcome suggestions that would aid us in meeting those needs.

name: CREATIVE ARTS CHRISTIAN ACADEMY, INC.
details:
Rely on Creative Arts Christian Academy for child care services, including an Academic program for Two's, Three's and Four's. We also offer an afterschool program, in Ridgeland, Mississippi. We  strive to provide the best care for children, ages six to eight years.  The one thing Creative Arts can promise all our parents is that the staff will LOVE your children.  Love for children and teaching is what brought all of us here.

May Sartin, Director and Owner, graduated in 1974 from Mississippi University for Women. She has a B.S. degree majoring in Child Development and has a minor in Psychology. In the last 37 years, "Miss May" has been a director, teacher, caregiver, business manager and owner. She started in child care in 1975 and bought Creative Arts in 1988.  Mrs. Sartin purchased this facility in 1993. Creative Arts is licensed by the State Board of Health.               Kristin Bulman, the Assistant Director, has been working in child care for 20 years.  She has worked in every aspect of childcare and  has worked at Creative Arts in the capacity of Assistant Director for 16 years,                                                                                                                              Our school, licensed since 1988, is founded on Christian values. We teach the ABeka Christian Curriculum to the two year class through the four year class and to the afterschoolers in the summer.                                                                                                                                                     Our staff are 20 years and older with many years of experience.  Federal and State background checks, using fingerprinting and the Child Abuse Registry, are required for all staff members to work with children. This check is done on every new employee and repeated every five years on existing employees. Each employee is required to have 15 hours of training every year and be CPR/First Aid certified. Most of the staff have been with us for at least five years to more than 25 years.

We support St. Jude Children's Research Hospital™ every summer with their Bike-A-Thon. We also visit local Nursing homes, work with MadCAAP at Thanksgiving and support our local Stewpot with food drives.

name: CREATIVE MINDS LEARNING CENTER, INC.
details: Quality child care with a strong emphasis on Early Childhood Education.

name: CROSSGATES BAPTIST KINDERGARTEN
details:
Crossgates Baptist Kindergarten is a place where children discover that it is fun to learn! Since learning is a lifelong process, we believe that a child’s first educational experiences should be positive, and active learning is much more valuable than passive learning.

At CBK, children want to come to school. They are loved and accepted as individuals, and important and valued as children that God has created. Their learning environment is rich in hands-on experiences which allow them to think and reason, and provides a wide variety of teaching materials, which encourages creativity and decision-making. Activities cover all curriculum areas and are based on what is appropriate for the child’s stage of development.

Children at Crossgates love to learn … and learn to love … like Jesus!

name: CROSSGATES METHODIST CHILDREN'S CENTER
details:
The Children's Center is known as the place to be for nurturing care for babies all the way through school age children.  We have a wonderful learning environment where all the important things are taught at each stage of development.   Our program is second to none, and in 2007, the Children’s Center was chosen to be a test site for establishing the Environment Rating Scales through the MSU Early Childhood Institute.  During the assessment, CMCC’s program scored a near perfect score, acknowledging the efforts of the excellent staff over the prior 15 years to provide a premiere program for early education.  The Quality Rating Systems program (QRS) is now offered throughout the state to help raise the standard of early care and education for all Mississippi’s children.  A copy of the CMCC Mission Statement is at the bottom of this page.   
 
Located at 21 Crossgates Drive in Brandon, The Children's Center opened in May 1992 as a ministry of Crossgates United Methodist Church to serve the Brandon community.  With full-time programs for children age six weeks to age four and an after school program, the Children’s Center currently serves almost 200 families in the community.  It is our mission to provide the highest quality of early childhood education for the children of Brandon, not only focusing on cognitive skills, but also physical, emotional, mental, social, and spiritual development.  We provide a safe, nurturing environment where children are encouraged to reach their fullest potential through learning activities and play.  Hours of operation for The Children’s Center are 6:30 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. Monday through Friday.  The Children’s Center is listed as a non-profit organization with the state of Mississippi.
 
We use Developmentally Appropriate Practice (DAP) as our curriculum guidelines, as well as The Early Learning Guidelines (ELGs) and the Early Learning Standards (ELSs) for the state of Mississippi.  Preschool classrooms use WEE Learn, which is a DAP bible-based curriculum.  From infants up to school age children, we want all the children to know of God's love for them!  DAP curriculum can also be known as learning center style, discovery or exploratory learning, and play-based learning.  Whatever you call it, research has shown that it is the VERY BEST way for young children to learn! 
 
We do have a waiting list in most age groups, so prospective parents are urged to plan a visit as soon as they know they will need a spot.  Scroll down this page for waiting list information which includes answers to many parent questions.  A visit to the Center is a must in order to get on the waiting list; at that time, CMCC Staff will be happy to extend a tour through the program.  Call to set up a tour; walk-ins are always welcome, but tours are not given during rest time.

Children of all faiths and nationalities are welcome.

We believe that each day should be filled with joy in learning, wonder, curiosity, and engaged investigation. We believe that children need time to acquire play skills so that they can learn to investigate, invent and problem-solve with complexity. We believe that the whole child’s body, soul and mind should be nurtured and challenged. We believe that teachers and families working together in partnership provide the highest quality preschool experience.

details: Hinds County Human Resource Agency (HCHRA) is a public non-profit organization established in 1976 by the Hinds County Mississippi Board of Supervisors. The Agency’s Central Administrative Office is located at 258 Maddox Road in Jackson, MS. To ensure that all area citizens have access to our programs and services, HCHRA has six Neighborhood Service Centers throughout rural Hinds County. name: EMERSON FAMILY SCHOOL
details:
Emerson Preschool is a licensed, fee-based preschool that provides  year-round comprehensive developmentally appropriate program for young children. Emerson is currently enrolling children ages 3 to 5.

The main goals of the program are:

    to help children feel good about themselves and others
    to become self-motivated learners
    to gain firm positive attitudes for future learning

Classes provide an environment that encourages children to express themselves through language, art, movement, music, dramatic play, and social interaction.  There is also a strong emphasis on literacy skills for 3-5 year olds.

Emerson has a well-qualified administrative and instructional staff.  The Principal, Dr. Joan Butler, has more than 30 years in administration of early childhood programs as an early childhood teacher, coordinator, and principal.

Mrs. Evans became a  Credentialed Director in 2007 and received her Child Development Associate Degree two years later to enhance her child care center. 
 
Our child care center focuses on problem solving, decision making and self-help, while promoting interpersonal communications.  These are key elements which contribute to the child’s development, self esteem and confidence.

We also provide a summer program for older children during summer vacations. Summer activities include many field trips and swimming at several local pools.

details: CCM is a ministry of the First Assembly of God Church. The center’s main mission is to assist families by providing a loving Christian environment for children 6 weeks through 12 years of age. We offer both full time and after school care.

name: FIRST BAPTIST CHILDCARE
details: Our church has a unique preschool ministry offered during the week for working parents. Children within our program are under the supervision of caring and trained adults dedicated to teaching each child about the gospel of Jesus as well as basic preschool education.

name: FIRST BAPTIST CHURCH KINDERGARTEN
details:
For over 25 years the FBC Taylorsville's Weekday Kindergarten ministry has been committed to the spiritual, mental, physical, and educational development of the children enrolled.

For more information about our program, contact the church office and talk to one of our directors: Sharon Skinner or Lynn Williamson. These ladies have years of experience and will be glad to assist you.

name: FIRST BAPTIST CHURCH OF BYRAM K/DAYCARE
FIRST BAPTIST CHURCH PRESCHOOL
details:
Purpose: To provide a Christian atmosphere, along with a safe and loving environment where children can learn.

Scope of Service: Two, Three, and Four-year old preschool program along with an optional lunch and extended care program.

Philosophy: Children should be provided a safe and loving environment where Christian ideals are taught, along with academics.

name: FIRST BAPTIST DAY CARE
details: Our Daycare and Kindergarten are ministries of First Baptist Church.   We, as early childhood professionals, set our goal not to simply be a substitute for parental care, but to be a partner team with parents to provide the best environment possible for your child.  Research has shown that the business of children is play; therefore, children learn primarily through play and activity—they need play to learn.  We strive to provide a great variety of learning experiences for the children in our care.  Although we understand the value of cognitive learning, we at First Baptist Preschool place a high value on the spiritual, social, emotional, and physical development for our children.

name: FIRST BAPTIST KINDERGARTEN
details:
Our goal is to provide experiences for Children that help parents point their children toward Christ so that one day, they will accept Him as their personal Savior and become life long disciples.
We have age graded Bible Study classes for all children on Sunday mornings during Adult Growth Group times.  We also have Pastor’s Pals binders available outside of the sanctuary for Children to help them engage during our worship services.  Pastor’s Pals binders include activities to help children listen and participate in worship in  child friendly way.  Activity boxes are also available for children who are not yet reading.  They contain activities and manipulatives to help them participate in worship.

name: FIRST BAPTIST KINDERGARTEN AND DAY CARE

OUR MISSION
Our desire is to provide support and encouragement to parents, while providing programs and activities that lay a strong spiritual foundation for children from birth to 6th grade.

name: FIRST DISCOVERY PRESCHOOL
details: First Discovery Preschool is our weekday, tuition-based preschool. We believe that home is the first and most important place for preschoolers to learn. However, many preschoolers reach a point where a more structured learning environment, with lots of friends, is desired. A good preschool experience opens the door to a lifelong love of learning.

name: FIRST FRIENDS, LLC CHILD CARE AND LEARNING CENTER
details: First Friends is a family owned and operated daycare facility. We put your child's needs first and provide a loving, nurturing, and safe environment for your little one. Over the last 22 years, First Friends has been selectively choosing staff members who have impressive backgrounds working with children. Know that all our staff all CPR trained and certified.  Together, our owner and director Robbie Parker and Teresa Hazel incorporate learning experiences with fun activities. We want your child to embrace education and enjoy themselves while doing so.

name: FIRST IMPRESSIONS DAYCARE AND LEARNING CENTER
FIRST NEW HOPE DAY CARE CENTER
FIRST PRESBYTERIAN CHILD DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM
details:
PCDP was established with the intent to provide high quality preschool instruction for young children, and to serve as an outreach mission of the church to the Columbus community. Recognizing the inborn worth and value of each child as a unique creation of God’s plan, we will strive to offer love and encouragement to every child.
Also known as PCDP, our preschool program is over 30 years old. We are currently a preschool only program, operating 8:30AM to 11:30AM Tuesday through Friday for 2 yr olds, 8:30AM to 11:30AM Monday through Friday for 3 yr olds and we offer both full and half day program options for 4 yr olds. Both our 3 and 4 yr old teachers hold degrees in early elementary education. Our classes are small with a 10 to 1 student/teacher ratio.

name: FIRST PRESBYTERIAN PRESCHOOL
details: The Preschool and Kindergarten programs at 1st Presbyterian Church in Tupelo are quality programs designed with the whole child in mind.  At our school, children are valued just as they are, and we take our responsibility to nurture and encourage them towards their full potential very seriously.  Our God-centered curriculum incorporates  language skills, literature study, art and music appreciation, social studies units, science study units, math skills, and the all important social skills development encouraged through free play, physical exercise, group games, and one-on-one interaction.  The goal of our educational model is to help children develop mentally, physically, socially, morally, and academically through an age-appropriate curriculum.  Our preschool age students are well-prepared for kindergarten, and our kindergarten students are well-prepared for first grade.For further information, please contact the church office at 842-5681 and ask to speak to our director Sunny Waters.  Classes are available for children ages 2 (as of Sept. 1) through kindergarten.  Our school year follows the Tupelo Public School District calendar with the exception of our opening (September rather than August) and our closing (usually 1 to 2 weeks before the end of the TPSD year).

Our Vision
Extending God's Divine Welcome to our neighbors and world by: INVITING people to join us in living under the rule of God; WELCOMING those who come with God's hospitality; NURTURING people in a Christian faith; EQUIPPING people by helping them discover their spiritual gifts; EMPOWERING people to be ministers of Jesus Christ; SENDING FORTH people to go into the world and live out our faith with boldness and compassion.
Our Purpose
A community of believers centered on God and focused on others.

name: GERTRUDE E. ELLIS HEAD START CENTER
details: Hinds County Human Resource Agency (HCHRA) is a public non-profit organization established in 1976 by the Hinds County Mississippi Board of Supervisors. The Agency’s Central Administrative Office is located at 258 Maddox Road in Jackson, MS. To ensure that all area citizens have access to our programs and services, HCHRA has six Neighborhood Service Centers throughout rural Hinds County. HCHRA also operates 13 Head Start Centers, three satellite Head Start Classrooms, and four Early Head Start Centers – all strategically located throughout Hinds County.

name: GOD'S LITTLE BUSY BEES CHILDCARE & LEARNING CENTER, INC.
GOOD SHEPHERD LUTHERAN PRESCHOOL
details:
Good Shepherd Lutheran Preschool is a mission ministry of Lutheran Church of the Good Shepherd-LCMS.  The church and school were founded in 1956. 

We are currently licensed to provide childcare services for 30 children through the Mississippi State Department of Health.  We have a Pre-K4 class with 16 children.  Our Pre-K3 preschool class has a capacity of 14 children. 

Our teaching staff are well trained and experienced in taking care of young children.  Our curriculum includes reading and writing lessons, math skills, science, art, music, and a daily Bible lesson.  We attend Chapel in our church sanctuary every week. 

Please contact our Director, Kristi Collins, to schedule a tour of our facility.

Our hours of operation are Monday - Friday, 8:00am - 11:30am.   We also have a "Lunch Bunch" available for on Tuesdays & Thursdays from 11:30am - 2:00pm.  Priority for the "Lunch Bunch" goes to our Pre-K4 students.

name: GRACE COMMUNITY SCHOOL
details: Basic to an accurate understanding of our educational objectives at Grace Community School is our philosophy that our primary objective as educators is to facilitate life change, as well as transfer to each student a thorough knowledge of the fullness of God’s love, which He brings to our school family. We maintain that such life change is only brought about through the empowering activity of the Holy Spirit, and we join with parents in seeking to lead students to that end.

name: GRENADA HEADSTART
details: The Office of Head Start states that Head Start is a school readiness program. Building upon this premise, ICS Head Start emphasizes and supports children's academic development, especially to significantly increase language development and to help preschoolers acquire the knowledge, skills, and attitudes that predict later success in reading, writing, mathematics, science, and social studies as they enter kindergarten.

name: HAPPY FACES DAY CARE AND LEARNING CENTER
HAPPY TIMES DAY CARE INC
details:
Happy Times Daycare has a beautiful center in Olive Branch, Mississippi.  We are licensed to accept children 6 weeks of age-12 years old without any discrimination. 

Our main objective is to provide a happy, healthy, and loving environment for your child.  As a parent you can rest assured that your child is receiving the best care and attention possible.

Recent studies reveal that children develop intellectually more during the first six years of their lives than any other time.  Children are born with a natural curiosity and desire to learn.  In order to stimulate a child's intellectual growth and encourage his imagination and curiosity, Happy Times offers a challenging and creative learning program.  The program consists of phonics, math concepts, science, social studies, arts and crafts, music, fine and gross motor skills, and field trips.  All programs are geared to the child's level, and each child is encouraged to progress at his or her own rate.  Our teachers present the programs in a fun and relaxed atmosphere.

Your child will also benefit by learning positive social behavior thus gaining a sense of respect for himself, his friends, and his surroundings.  One of our main goals is to instill in each child a sense of self-worth and a good self concept.  We accomplish this by using a positive approach toward learning and discipline.  Discipline is handled with behavior modification and time out.

A well balanced, nourishing lunch and two snacks are served every day.  Menus are posted so you can see what your child is eating.  Also, an optional breakfast is served between 7:30am-8:00am for a rate of $1 per day.

name: HERITAGE CHILDREN'S CENTER
details:
The Mission of Heritage Children’s Center is to provide high-quality, innovative after school and summer day camp programs for families in our community in an environment of acceptance and trust.


Serving the Laurel/Jones County area, the programs at Heritage Children’s Center are aimed at kids ages 5-12, focusing on individual development and growth through active play and hands-on learning opportunities.


At Heritage Children's Center, it is our deeply held conviction that children are indeed "a gift of God." This belief is foundational to why and how we do what we do at HCC.

Through a program based upon your child’s needs and abilities, we plan to help your preschooler become a confident and happy child ready for the next stage of their educational, emotional, and spiritual development.

We offer 3K classes for children who are age 3 by September 1st of the current year; 4K classes for children who are 4 by September 1st, and 5K classes for children who are 5 by the same date. details: John Hopkins Elementary School was built in 1978. John Hopkins is an urban elementary school and is a part of the Jackson Public School District. The school is located on 170 John Hopkins Avenue in the far northwestern corner of Jackson on the border of the city of Clinton. The school plant covers 66,664 square feet with 42 classrooms, a media center, cafetorium, and office space on a campus of 6.9 acres. John Hopkins currently has one Pre-K class, three kindergarten classes, three first grade classes, three second grade classes, three third grade classes, three fourth grade classes, three fifth grade classes, two self-contained exceptional education classes, one music classroom, one counselor classroom, one in-school suspension classroom, one Open Doors classroom, and one speech therapy classroom. The mission of John Hopkins Elementary School is  to provide a quality education for all students by promoting positive behavior,  maintaining a safe and orderly environment, and acquiring a knowledge base to become a lifelong learner.

name: JONESTOWN HEAD START
JPS CDC CHILD CARE PROGRAM
details: The Early Childhood Education Curriculum prepares students for future success in the field of early childhood education by improving academic and technology skills, improving employability skills, and articulations with community colleges. This rigorous and relevant 2-year program is based on state and national standards, CDA (Child Development Associate) competency standards, NAEYC (National Association for the Education of Young Children) standards, and 21st century workforce skills. The course is a 2-year program offering 4 Carnegie units of credit. The industry of early childhood education is preparing for changes due to high rates of teacher retirement, national and state initiatives and requirements, and the new focus on the field of early childhood education.

name: JUST KIDS AND COMPUTERS, INC.
details:
Our child care, preschool, and after school programs are designed with young children in mind. We strive to provide learning experiences that are both fun and educational.  We also strive to provide an atmosphere of love and trust to help children feel comfortable coming into our program.

The Learning Depot is more than a daycare, it's an early education center, and environment in which your child can grow, blossom, and enjoy the excitement and wonders of childhood. For twenty-two years we have given parents of the Mississippi Gulf Coast the peace of mind knowing that their children are truly being given the highest quality in early childhood development programs.

name: MADISON COUNTY GYMNASTICS
details:
Begin your gymnastics career today at Madison County Gymnastics! With more than 25 years of experience and knowledge, we have been providing classes and routines in the Madison, Ridgeland, Jackson, Brandon, Pearl and Gluckstadt area. At Madison County Gymnastics, we have worked with many families to improve their gymnastic skills, no matter what level.

The staff at Madison County Gymnastics is certified and trained. We are professional members of USAG and the Mississippi State Board of Health.

Schedule your free visit to our facility today to see what we’re all about. We look forward to seeing you soon!

Our building is approximately 9000 sq. ft. and is heated and air conditioned.  Our staff is dedicated to offering all of our students a safe, happy, and productive gymnastics experience. We offer both recreational and competitive gym classes for girls ages 3 -18.  To be a member of a competitive team, you must tryout or be advanced through our recreational class program. name: MCCALL HEAD START CENTER
details:
Friends of Children of Mississippi (FCM), Inc. is a highly efficient, team-based, non-profit human service organization.

Our mission is to strengthen children and families through community partnerships by:

    Assisting families to become self-sufficient and serving as advocates for children and families.

We increase families’ capacity to support and nurture their children by developing a compassionate partnership between staff and families, which recognizes parents as the primary educators of their children.

In support of this partnership, FCM, Inc. provides opportunities for continuous staff development and growth and creates an environment that promotes job satisfaction and community service.

MAP believes that every child deserves a head start in life -- an equal opportunity to develop character, talent, mind, body and personality.

We further believe that we are to prepare children to function in our society by providing life experiences. As America's greatest resource, children will ultimately determine the destiny of our country. All children have a unique contribution to make to society. MAP is dedicated to maximizing the disadvantaged child's potential for contributing.

The American dream of freedom, justice and equal opportunity for all is being brought nearer to reality in Mississippi as dedicated MAP personnel interact with other agencies to accomplish this goal.

By doingso, we open up opportunities for lo income parents to work and go to school, while at the same time offering valuable learning experiences for their children.

The MCH Child Care Food Program provides each enrolled child with nutritious food and supports nutrition education. Our Comprehensive Family Services councelors assess the specific needs of individual families and then develop a holistic approach that responds directly to those needs. Our Expectant Mothers Program offers parenting training and gives expectant mothers experience with toddlers and infants. Following birth, MCH works with the mother and child over a three year journey of positive development. Finally, MCH helps build relationships between women and employers through Employment and Training Referrals for parents of children in our Early Headstart program. Together, these programs offer our families the support they need to break the cycle of poverty.

details:
At Open Arms, we believe in creating an environment that will enhance a child’s intellectual, emotional, social and physical growth. Our program involves instructing play by providing activities (Art, water play, table toys, puzzles, books, blocks, dramatic play, cooking and baking, outdoor play, etc.) as well as taking advantage of incidental or child introduced play times without reducing or inhibiting the child’s enjoyment. We feel that the child learns through play and through instruction. In other words, each child may explore and manipulate the materials at hand to develop and understanding trial and error.
We also feel that it is important for each child to receive the nurturing and emotional guidance that is often needed at this stage of development. We hope to convey a loving and supportive atmosphere that will encourage each individual child to feel a sense of worth.

We aim to be much more than a child care center. We want to provide and model the best in early childhood education, combined with nuturing all children's needs. As early childhood educators, we strive to offer a developmentally appropriate and stimulating curriculum in a classroom setting that seeks to provide the warmth and security of a child's home. The environment that your child will encounter is an exciting one, full of materials to manipulate and that will allow for creative play and opportunities to create and explore with paint, clay and other media.

We believe that play is essential to the young child. Through play, young children learn to make sense of their physical, social and curtural environment.  Children develop cooperation, an enthusiasm for learning, creative thinking and problem solving skills through play situations that are carefully structured by experienced teachers.  We encourge children to express feelings such as sadness, fear, love, anger and happiness.  We beleive the development of these skills will assist children in continuing their education and forming peer relationships with confidence.

It is our intention to provide opportunities for parents to meet and discuss common concerns with teachers and staff to help gain more understanding of child developement, particularly as it applies to their child. We encourage you to visit any time and to join us for field trips and special family events at our center.

Your child will receive loving, personal attention from our experienced staff to prepare them for their eventual transition to school. The Privette School prides itself on implementing the Reggio Emilia educational approach, which allows children to express themselves using “a thousand languages.”

Breakfast, lunch and two daily snacks are freshly-prepared by our school cook with health-consciousness in mind. Children are encouraged to drink water instead of sugary drinks. They’re also introduced to a variety of new foods.

At our church-based school, even the smallest children take part in visual arts, music and theatrical performances throughout the year. You’ll be surprised how much a preschooler can ham it up onstage!

Our school is convenient to almost everything in Jackson. We are located in the Fondren neighborhood on the west side of Interstate 55 just north of Meadowbrook Road and just south of Northside Drive. We are located in the Broadmeadow United Methodist Church building and we are a ministry of the church.

name: CLIFTON PRESTON, SR HEAD START CENTER
details:
The purpose of our PRVO Policy Council is to serve as a link between public and private organizations, the grantee board of directors, the communities served, and the children enrolled in the planning and coordinating of the Head Start Program in Lamar, Marion, Pike, Stone and Walthall Counties in the State of Mississippi.

PRVO Policy Council is chosen from the Parent Committees (parents) and recommendations from major agencies of the communities and counties served for Community Representatives.  PRVO Policy Council Committee is comprised of twenty (20) members with 51 percent of the membership being parents of children currently enrolled.  These members represent each of our fourteen (14) Head Start Centers, one Liaison, one Early Head Start and five (5) Community Representatives.  Our Policy Council consists of twenty-one (21) members with Jennifer Gayden as our Chairperson.

Regular meetings are held every third (3rd) Monday.  In the event of a holiday on that Monday, the meeting is usually moved to Tuesday.  Per Bylaws, there is no meeting in June, July or December.  However, a “special call” meeting can be held in either of those months.  A majority of the members of the Policy Council must be present to constitute a quorum for regular or special meetings to transact business.

name: NEW BEGINNINGS LEARNING CENTER
details:
We believe in a caring and positive atmosphere, we create a warm and happy place for preschoolers to learn. As we bridge the gap from home to school, we guide children to a continued good self-image, while building social skills that will follow them in school and out of school settings.

Sensory, motor, perceptual and language skills are introduced through materials and activities which are both child-centered and teacher-directed. Work is planned which emphasizes the process rather than the product, fostering a sense of accomplishment and pride.

Based on the theory that children learn through experiences; therefore, sensitivity to the value of play is required, for it is through play that children create their own meaning and learning schemes. Play is the work of the children. Classroom routines encourage active involvement, meaningful experimentation and reinforcement through repetition. Schedules are designed which balance structure and free choice, as well as active and quiet times.

name: CHICKASAW NATION HEAD START
details:
The Chickasaw Nation Head Start is a center-based federal and tribally funded program that promotes the school readiness of children from ages three to five years. The Head Start philosophy is based on the principle that early childhood education should address children’s needs in all areas of development: physical, social, emotional and cognitive. It should provide support and assistance to all those who affect the child’s development. The child’s entire family, as well as the community, must be involved.

The Chickasaw Nation Head Start program is family-focused. The family is viewed as the most important influence in a child’s life. To meet these needs, the Head Start program offers components in education, parent/ guardian involvement, health, social services and services for children with disabilities. Through an interdisciplinary approach of all components and parent policy council group, this philosophy is reflected in every aspect of the Head Start experience. The Head Start environment will provide children the opportunity to develop to their maximum potential.

name: ARDMORE DAY NURSERY INC.
details:
Ardmore Day Nursery has been in continuous operations since 1950, but what most people don’t realize is that Ardmore Day Nursery was first originated in 1919 but closed in 1928.

On May 17, 1950 a group of women representing the Women’s Clubs of Ardmore met at the YWCA in response to a call from the American Association of University Women to organize a nursery for the working mothers of the area whose children needed daycare.

October 1, 1950, the Ardmore Day Nursery was reborn in a house donated by Mr. and Mrs. Wirt Franklin.  Located at 321 C Street NW, twenty nine children ages 3 to 6 were enrolled.  The cost by this time had risen to one dollar per day.  The nursery remained at the 321 C Street NW location for the next 31 years.

In 1981 a large anonymous donation was given to the nursery for a new building.  The new groundbreaking was on January 25, 1982.  This new building was built on the opposite end of the property located at 320 D Street NW where it remains today.

Our current Board of Directors continues in the tradition of making sure the Ardmore Day Nursery remains a part of the community by providing the venues to make the funds necessary to run the nursery.

"I think what sets us apart, is not only the quality of care but the dedication of our board and our staff.  We try to establish a close-knit family relationship with our parents and their children so they feel they are always welcome.  Our staff knows taking care of these children is more than just a job.” - Rae Best
